

---
const pageTitle = "Mirror";
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <title>{pageTitle}</title>
    <style>
      :root {
        --paper: #ffffff;
        --ink: #000000;
        --line: #000000;
        --soft: #efefef;
        --blue: #0000ee;
        --red: #cc0000;
        --green: #008000;
      }

      html, body {
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        background: var(--paper);
        color: var(--ink);
        font-family: "Times New Roman", Times, serif;
        font-size: 18px;
        line-height: 1.55;
      }

      a { text-decoration: underline; }
      a.blue { color: var(--blue); }
      a.red { color: var(--red); }
      a.green { color: var(--green); }

      .page {
        width: min(900px, calc(100% - 48px));
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 28px 0 60px;
      }

      .topbar {
        border: 1px solid var(--line);
        padding: 10px 14px;
        margin-bottom: 18px;
        text-align: center;
        background: #fafafa;
      }

      .topbar span {
        display: inline-block;
        margin: 0 8px;
        white-space: nowrap;
      }

      .frame {
        border: 1px solid var(--line);
        padding: 22px 24px 28px;
        position: relative;
        overflow: hidden;
      }

      .symbol-bg {
        position: absolute;
        top: 50%;
        left: 50%;
        transform: translate(-50%, -50%) rotate(4deg);
        font-size: 250px;
        opacity: 0.12;
        pointer-events: none;
        user-select: none;
        z-index: 0;
      }

      .content-layer {
        position: relative;
        z-index: 1;
      }

      h1 {
        font-size: 40px;
        line-height: 1.05;
        text-align: center;
        margin: 0 0 8px;
        font-weight: bold;
      }

      .subtitle {
        text-align: center;
        font-size: 16px;
        margin: 0 0 24px;
      }

      .divider {
        text-align: center;
        margin: 18px 0 24px;
        letter-spacing: 1px;
      }

      p { margin: 0 0 16px; }

      .quote {
        margin: 22px auto;
        max-width: 680px;
        border: 1px solid var(--line);
        padding: 14px 16px;
        background: var(--soft);
        font-style: italic;
        text-align: center;
      }

      .section-title {
        font-size: 28px;
        text-align: center;
        margin: 34px 0 16px;
        font-weight: bold;
      }

      .mini-links {
        text-align: center;
        margin-top: 30px;
        font-size: 16px;
      }

      .mini-links a {
        display: inline-block;
        margin: 4px 10px;
      }

      .footer-note {
        text-align: center;
        margin-top: 26px;
        font-size: 14px;
      }

      @media (max-width: 700px) {
        html, body { font-size: 17px; }
        h1 { font-size: 32px; }
        .frame { padding: 18px 16px 24px; }
        .symbol-bg { font-size: 180px; }
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="page">
      <div class="topbar">
        <span>[ <a class="blue" href="/">home</a> ]</span>
        <span>[ <a class="blue" href="/symbols/">symbols index</a> ]</span>
        <span>[ <a class="green" href="/symbols/labyrinth">previous</a> ]</span>
        <span>[ <a class="red" href="/symbols/fire">next</a> ]</span>
      </div>

      <main class="frame">
        <div class="symbol-bg">🪞</div>

        <div class="content-layer">
          <h1>Mirror</h1>
          <p class="subtitle">symbols / reflection / truth / archive entry 007</p>

          <div class="divider">***</div>

          <p>
            The mirror is a symbol of reflection. It shows what is present without
            adding or removing anything. Because of this, it is often linked to truth,
            but also to illusion, depending on what is being seen.
          </p>

          <p>
            What appears in the mirror is not separate from the one who looks.
            The image reflects something already there, but it may not always be
            recognized immediately.
          </p>

          <div class="quote">
            the mirror does not change what is seen, but it reveals what is already present.
          </div>

          <h2 class="section-title">self and reflection</h2>

          <p>
            Psychologically, the mirror represents self-seeing. This can come through
            direct awareness, but also through other people, dreams, and situations
            that reflect aspects of oneself.
          </p>

          <p>
            Sometimes what is reflected is accepted. Other times it is resisted.
            This resistance often reveals something that has not yet been integrated.
          </p>

          <h2 class="section-title">truth and illusion</h2>

          <p>
            The mirror can reveal truth, but it can also distort if what is being
            perceived is filtered through expectation or fear. Because of this,
            the mirror is tied to both clarity and deception.
          </p>

          <p>
            To see clearly requires not only looking, but also the ability to remain
            with what is seen without immediately changing it.
          </p>

          <div class="mini-links">
            <a class="blue" href="/symbols/">back to symbols index</a>
            <a class="blue" href="/symbols/fire">continue to: fire</a>
            <a class="red" href="/symbols/labyrinth">labyrinth</a>
          </div>

          <p class="footer-note">
            this page is part of the hidden archive.
          </p>
        </div>
      </main>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>